HDIW Question 1

This question refers to a chapter in the book that I only skimmed, so Ill take a wild guess and that is: with Event Studies you have to assume without much evidence that the trend pre-event would have continued into the future had the event not happened; but with diff-in-diff, you have evidence from a comparable untreated group that supports that assumption.

HDIW Question 2

The back door through Time is closed (B).

HDIW Question 3

  1. The untreated group could have changed, in a way unrelated to the treatment, around the same time that treatment occured. An example of this: youre looking at how the implementation of public smoking laws in restaurants affects the prevalence of smokers, comparing Ohio and Indiana before and after Ohio implemented public smoking laws. Indiana did not implement these laws, and smoking was equally prevalent over time in both states prior to treatment. However, it just so happens that Indiana raised taxes on cigarettes in the same year that Ohio introduced the public smoking laws. That means that the parallel trends would break at the time of treatment.
  2. Itll be off by however much the untreated group deviated from their previous trend (in the example above, itll be off by however much cigarette taxes affected the prevalence of smokers).

HDIW Question 4

  1. No - the gap between them is narrowing anyway.
  2. Underestimate - even if the treated group improves a tiny bit more than the untreated, thats more than a tiny difference, because it had to overcome the converging pre-treatment trends.

HDIW Question 5

My hesitation with this design is that many states in the U.S. actually loosened restrictions at the end of May/beginning of June 2020, so a diff-in-diff might overestimate the effect of restrictions in Canada. Additionally, I would want to use a method that allows for dynamic treatment effects; its possible that new restrictions take a while to be reflected in the case counts.

HDIW Question 6

Diff-in-Diff = Effect on Treated Group - Time Effect = (9-5) - (7.5-6) = 4 - 1.5 = 2.5

HIIP Question 2

HIIP Question 3

This test is called the placebo test, and it is performed in order to check the parallel trends assumption. If we got a high value for \(\beta_3\) on this test, it means we found a treatment effect without a treatment at all, which is bad for our identification of the actual treatment effect.

HIIP Question 4

  1. The fact that the CI for Y at \(t_1\) is above zero is concerning, but not necessarily a dealbreaker.
  2. The treatment effect of Y is immediately 3 units, but is short-lasting, with effects returning to near-zero within 3 periods of treatment.

HIIP Question 5

Thats concerning if the treatment effect is dynamic. For example, in the graph for HIIP question 4 above, if the treated group was used as a control, the (treated) control would be expected to trend downward on Y while the (as yet untreated) treated group wouldnt be; that would break parallel trends and overestimate the immediate treatment effect.

Coding Question 4

sr <- sr |> 
  mutate(Treated = if_else(keyword == "sourdough", 1, 0),
         after = if_else(date > "2020-03-15", 1, 0))
srtest <- sr |> 
  filter(after == 0)

lm(hits ~ date + date:Treated,
   data = srtest) |> 
  summary()

Coding Question 5

srm <- sr |> 
  mutate(dateshift = date - days(15),
         month = if_else(month(dateshift) == 12, 0, month(dateshift)),
         month = month-2,
         Treatment = Treated == 1 & after == 1) |> 
  select(-dateshift)

feols(hits ~ Treatment | keyword + month,
      data = srm,
      vcov = "cluster")

Coding Question 7

coefplot(dfe)

The effect looks like its strongest and most statistically significant right away, and then eventually tapers off, like the overall shape of the data suggested in the beginning. The first two points are a little off from zero, although their confidence intervals do include zerolets try it without soup, just to see.

srm2 <- srm |> 
  filter(!(keyword == "soup"))

dfe2 <- feols(hits ~ i(month, Treated, ref = 0) | 
            keyword + month, 
            data = srm2,
            vcov = "cluster")

coefplot(dfe2)

Awesome!!! Looks like that made our pre-treatment estimates closer to 0, and also revealed more of the effect of the pandemic. It looks like it does taper off slightly after the initial bump, but lands at a higher value than before the pandemic.
